      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Unread Book: Good Intentions Count, Too</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Gene Dunn letter comments on July 15 article on best-selling books that are seldom read</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Let Us Now Praise Books Well Sold, Well Loved but Seldom Read,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, July 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Let Us Now Praise Books Well Sold, Well Loved but Seldom Read,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, July 15):</p>
        <p>To those who remain sheepish about their unfinished reading, take heart.</p>
        <p>Walter Benjamin, in his ''Illuminations,'' recounts the story about Anatole France, who was asked about his library:</p>
        <p>''And you have read all these books, Monsieur France?''</p>
        <p>His response: ''Not one-tenth of them. I don't suppose you use your Sevres china every day?''</p>
        <p>GENE DUNN  Elgin, Ill., July 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
